hire): habitational name from the city of Norwich in Norfolk. The placename derives from Old English <i>north</i> ‘north, northern’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘specialized or outlying farm’."],"variants":[{"name":"Northridge","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Norridge in Upton Scudamore (Wiltshire) or from a similarly named but unidentified places elsewhere. The placename derives from Middle English <i>north</i> ‘north’ + <i>rigge</i> ‘ridge’ (Old English <i>north</i>, <i>hrycg</i>). There may have been some confusion with   Norwich  ."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":69,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Herbert de Norwich was born about 1190, in Norwich, Norfolk, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Herbert de Norwich."},"et":{"about 1190–":"umbes 1190–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1224":"1224","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norf